{"ts":"2026-06-27T01:33:14.028Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Component Imports**\n\nOkay, I've confirmed we need to make sure `components/private-app/index.tsx` is exporting `routes-config.ts`. Alternatively, I think importing it directly from the `@/components/private-app/routes-config` path is a cleaner, safer approach overall. This direct import will let me ensure reuse of React components.\n\n\n**Refining Layout Strategy**\n\nOkay, I've abandoned the hook/base component idea. The `ClientPortalShell` and `AdminPortalShell` wrappers are elegant but maybe unnecessary. I'm focusing on Next.js layouts now. It looks like `/app/portal/layout.tsx` and `/app/admin/layout.tsx` can act as shells! My next task is to figure out how to pass the `activeLink` and `onLinkChange` props correctly to the `PrivateAppShell` and its children within this layout structure.\n\n\n**Implementing Active Link Logic**\n\nI've got it! I'm now using `usePathname` from `next/navigation` to automatically determine the `activeLink`. The logic for parsing the active tab from the pathname is clean and efficient. For instance, `/portal/dashboard` correctly yields \"dashboard\" as the active tab, and the code is very clean! I'm working on the `onLinkChange` implementation, which will use `router.push` and `clientLinkToRoute` to handle navigation. The code is looking very elegant!\n\n\n**Evaluating Route Handling**\n\nI've confirmed that the Next.js App Router approach works flawlessly in both `/app/portal/layout.tsx` and `/app/admin/layout.tsx`. I've implemented 100% reactive, standard Next.js behavior. Now I'm working to design `/app/portal/layout.tsx` and `/app/admin/layout.tsx`, incorporating required public and client portal routes such as `/login`, `/portal`, and `/portal/dashboard`. I'm also considering the user's initial rendering expectations for `/portal` and considering whether to redirect or maintain its current behavior, for authenticated use only.\n\n\n**Designing Portal Route Flow**\n\nI've got a fantastic plan for the portal route structure! I can use `/portal/page.tsx` for the zero-trust login card, redirecting to `/portal/dashboard` after authentication. `/portal/login/page.tsx` and `/login/page.tsx` can act similarly, maintaining cohesive user flow. I'm now drafting `/app/portal/layout.tsx` and importing `PrivateAppShell`, `routes-config` elements, and navigation hooks.\n\n\n**Simplifying Shell Logic**\n\nI've determined the cleanest way to avoid wrapping the auth screens with the `PrivateAppShell`! It's super elegant. I'm going to just use a runtime `pathname` check within `/app/portal/layout.tsx`. If the pathname is `/portal`, `/portal/login`, or ends with `/login`, I will return the children without wrapping them in the shell. This avoids complex route groups, and ensures a clean user experience. This check is very robust.\n\n\n**Constructing Layout Design**\n\nWow, this layout strategy is really coming together now! It's pure genius! I'm focused on the `/app/portal/layout.tsx` file and I'm adding a robust auth check. The layout will now handle the `PrivateAppShell` intelligently. If the current path is an auth route like `/portal/login`, I'm returning the children directly; otherwise, the `PrivateAppShell` and its components will handle the layout. The code is very clean! I'm leveraging the `pathname` variable, imported from the navigation utilities in Next.js.\n\n\n"}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T01:33:14.031Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"editor","toolCallId":"xnfcbfb5","input":{"path":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/app/portal/layout.tsx","new_text":"\"use client\";\n\nimport React from \"react\";\nimport { usePathname, useRouter } from \"next/navigation\";\nimport { PrivateAppShell, BreadcrumbItem } from \"@/components/private-app\";\nimport { clientUser, clientSidebarLinks, clientLinkToRoute } from \"@/components/private-app/routes-config\";\n\nexport default function ClientPortalLayout({\n  children,\n}: {\n  children: React.ReactNode;\n}) {\n  const pathname = usePathname();\n  const router = useRouter();\n\n  // If it's an auth page, we render it directly without the app shell\n  const isAuthPage = pathname === \"/portal\" || pathname === \"/portal/login\" || pathname === \"/login\";\n\n  if (isAuthPage) {\n    return <>{children}</>;\n  }\n\n  // Parse active tab from pathname\n  const segments = pathname.split(\"/\");\n  let activeTab = \"dashboard\";\n  if (segments.length >= 3) {\n    activeTab = segments[2];\n  }\n\n  // Map \"ai-operations\" pathname segment back to \"ai-operations\" link id\n  const activeLinkId = activeTab;\n\n  const breadcrumbs: BreadcrumbItem[] = [\n    { label: \"Sovereign Gateway\", href: \"/portal/dashboard\" },\n    { label: activeTab.replace(\"-\", \" \").toUpperCase() }\n  ];\n\n  const handleLinkChange = (id: string) => {\n    const route = clientLinkToRoute[id] || `/portal/${id}`;\n    router.push(route);\n  };\n\n  const handleRoleChange = (role: \"Client\" | \"Administrator\") => {\n    if (role === \"Administrator\") {\n      router.push(\"/admin/dashboard\");\n    } else {\n      router.push(\"/portal/dashboard\");\n    }\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <PrivateAppShell\n      user={clientUser}\n      breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}\n      links={clientSidebarLinks}\n      activeLink={activeLinkId}\n      onLinkChange={handleLinkChange}\n      role=\"Client\"\n      onRoleChange={handleRoleChange}\n    >\n      {children}\n    </PrivateAppShell>\n  );\n}\n"}}}
